<HEAD>CONTENTS.</HEAD>
<LIST>
<LABEL>PART I.</LABEL>
<ITEM><HI>OF the End and Efficacy of Satire.</HI> The Love of Glory and Fear of Shame univer&s;al, &vers; <HI>29.</HI> This Pa&s;&s;ion, implanted in Man as a Spur to Virtue, is gene|rally perverted, &vers; <HI>41.</HI> And thus becomes the Occa&s;ion of the greate&s;t Follies, Vices, and Mi&s;eries, &vers; <HI>61.</HI> It is the Work of <HI>Satire</HI> to rectify this Pa&s;&s;ion, to reduce it to its proper Channel, and to convert it into an Incentive to Wi&s;|dom and Virtue, &vers; <HI>89.</HI> Hence it appears that <HI>Satire</HI> may influence tho&s;e who defy all Laws Human and Divine, &vers; <HI>99.</HI> An objection an&s;wered, &vers; <HI>131.</HI></ITEM>
<LABEL>PART II.</LABEL>
<ITEM><HI>Rules for the Conduct of Satire.</HI> Ju&s;tice and Truth its chief and e&s;&s;ential Property, &vers; <HI>169.</HI> Prudence in the Application of Wit and Ridicule, who&s;e Province is, not to <HI>explore</HI> unknown, but to <HI>enforce</HI> known Truths, &vers; <HI>191.</HI> Proper Subjects of <HI>Satire</HI> are the Manners of pre&s;ent times, &vers; <HI>239.</HI> Decency of Expre&s;&s;ion recommended, &vers; <HI>255.</HI> The different Methods in which Folly and Vice ought to be cha&s;|ti&s;ed, &vers; <HI>269.</HI> The Variety of Style and Manner which the&s;e two Subjects require, &vers; <HI>277.</HI> The Prai&s;e of Virtue may be admitted with Propriety, &vers; <HI>315.</HI> Caution with regard to Panegyrick, &vers; <HI>329.</HI> The Dignity of <HI>true Sa|tire,</HI> &vers; <HI>341.</HI></ITEM>
<LABEL><PB N="iv" REF="8">
PART III.</LABEL>
<ITEM><HI>The Hi&s;tory of Satire. Roman</HI> Satiri&s;ts, <HI>Lucilius, Horace, Per&s;ius, Juvenal, &vers; 357,</HI> etc. Cau&s;es of the Decay of Literature, particularly of <HI>Satire, &vers; 389.</HI> Re|vival of <HI>Satire, &vers; 401. Era&s;mus</HI> one of its principal Re&s;torers, &vers; <HI>405. Donne, &vers; 411.</HI> The Abu&s;e of Satire in <HI>England,</HI> during the licentious Reign of <HI>Charles II. &vers; 415. Dryden, &vers; 429.</HI> The true Ends of <HI>Satire</HI> pur|&s;ued by <HI>Boileau</HI> in <HI>France, &vers; 439;</HI> and by Mr. <HI>Pope</HI> in <HI>England, &vers; 445.</HI></ITEM>
