<ARGUMENT>
<HEAD>ARGUMENT.</HEAD>
<P>Of the <HI>U&s;e</HI> of <HI>RICHES.</HI></P>
<P>THAT it is known to few, mo&s;t falling into one of the extremes, <HI>Avarice</HI> or <HI>Profu&s;ion,</HI> &vers; 1, &amp;c. The Point di&s;cu&s;s'd, whether the invention of Money has been more commodious, or pernicious to Mankind, &vers; <HI>21 to 77.</HI> That Riches, either to the <HI>Avaricious</HI> or the <HI>Prodigal,</HI> cann$t afford Happine&s;s, &s;carcely Nece&s;&s;aries, &vers; <HI>89 to 160.</HI> That Avarice is an ab&s;olute Frenzy, without an End or Purpo&s;e, &vers; <HI>113, &amp;c. 152.</HI> Conjectures about the Mo|tives of Avaricious men, &vers; <HI>121 to 153.</HI> That the con|duct of men, with re&s;pect to Riches, can only be accounted for by the <HI>ORDER OF PROVIDENCE,</HI> which works the general Good out of Extremes, and brings all to its great End by perpetual Revolutions, &vers; <HI>161 to 178.</HI> How a <HI>Mi&s;er</HI> acts upon Principles which appear to him rea&s;on|able, &vers; <HI>179.</HI> How a <HI>Prodigal</HI> does the &s;ame, &vers; <HI>199.</HI> The due Medium, and true u&s;e of Riches, &vers; <HI>219.</HI> The <HI>Man</HI> of <HI>Ro&s;s, &vers; 250.</HI> The fate of the <HI>Profu&s;e</HI> and the <HI>Covetous,</HI> in two examples; both mi&s;erable in Life and in Death, &vers; <HI>300,</HI> &amp;c. The Story of Sir <HI>Balaam, &vers; 339 to the end.</HI></P>
</ARGUMENT>
<P></P>
